A binary tree is a data structure where each item (called a node) has a value and can have up to two "children" nodes, typically referred to as the left child and the right child. It starts with a single root node, and each child can itself be the root of a smaller binary tree, forming a branching, hierarchical structure.

```json
{
  "value": 10,
  "left": {
    "value": 5,
    "left": {
      "value": 2,
      "left": null,
      "right": null
    },
    "right": {
      "value": 7,
      "left": null,
      "right": null
    }
  },
  "right": {
    "value": 15,
    "left": null,
    "right": null
  }
}
```

The tree I just output has the root node with a value of 10. The root's left child is a node with value 5, and this node itself has two children: a left child with value 2 and a right child with value 7. The root's right child is a single node with value 15, which has no children. So, the tree has a total of 5 nodes, with the node containing 5 being the only one with two children.

